docs.abstract: A $35 million plan to redevelop one of Louisville’s oldest and poorest neighborhoods is threatened by the coronavirus outbreak.
docs.snippet: A $35 million plan to redevelop one of Louisville’s oldest and poorest neighborhoods is threatened by the coronavirus outbreak.
docs.lead_paragraph: LOUISVILLE, Ky. — Until the coronavirus pandemic, Gill Holland spent six years and $35 million constructing new residences and renovating 19th- and 20th-century warehouses in Portland, a historic neighborhood on the Ohio River that is Louisville’s oldest and one of its poorest.

headline.main: Unease at Kentucky Project Mirrors Construction Industry’s Fears

docs.abstract: Natural-gas companies operating in the state were looking shaky before the coronavirus hit. Local economies are now at risk.
docs.snippet: Natural-gas companies operating in the state were looking shaky before the coronavirus hit. Local economies are now at risk.
docs.lead_paragraph: CARMICHAELS, Pa. — The last time the global economy was in free fall, an economic savior showed up in southwestern Pennsylvania. Energy companies, which had discovered a way to get at the state’s vast natural-gas reserves, invested billions of dollars in the region, cushioning the blow of the Great Recession.

headline.main: Fracking Once Lifted Pennsylvania. Now It Could Be a Drag.

docs.lead_paragraph: We are holding a conference call for DealBook readers tomorrow, April 2, at 11 a.m. Eastern. Our special guest will be Maggie Haberman, one of the NYT’s top White House correspondents. You’ll be able to ask Maggie about her reporting during the call, or submit questions in advance to dealbook@nytimes.com. For details about how to join, visit the R.S.V.P. page.
